docs.lead_paragraph: Sandra Fluke, who was subjected to degrading comments by Rush Limbaugh after she tried to testify in Congress about insurance coverage for contraceptives, is running for a seat in the State Senate.

headline.main: Once Targeted by Limbaugh, Lawyer Seeks California Seat
headline.print_headline: Once Targeted by Limbaugh, Lawyer Seeks California Seat

docs.abstract: Lawyer Sandra Fluke, Democrat, will seek California State Senate seat representing some of most affluent sections of Los Angeles County; Fluke gained national attention after being denied chance to testify before a congressional committee about wanting her college's health plan to cover contraceptives, and was subsequently subjected to degrading comments by Rush Limbaugh.
docs.snippet: Sandra Fluke, who was subjected to degrading comments by Rush Limbaugh after she tried to testify in Congress about insurance coverage for contraceptives, is running for a seat in the State Senate.

docs.lead_paragraph: Flush with money and momentum, Republicans are confident that they can at least maintain the gains they made in governors' races four years ago.

headline.main: Republicans Replay 2010 Strategy at State Level
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Replays 2010 Strategy at State Level

docs.abstract: Republican gubernatorial candidates have built unexpectedly strong position for election in fall 2014, helped by improving economy, disaffection with Pres Obama and national fund-raising machine that is leagues ahead of their Democratic Party opponents; Republicans are faced with defending 22 of 36 governorships that will be up for grabs in November, led by New Jersey Gov Chris Christie, who is rebounding from scandal.
docs.snippet: Flush with money and momentum, Republicans are confident that they can at least maintain the gains they made in governors' races four years ago.

docs.lead_paragraph: Paperwork required to opt out of coverage is part of a struggle to balance religious freedom and women’s rights.

headline.main: A Two-Page Form Spawns a Contraceptive Showdown
headline.print_headline: A Two-Page Form Spawns an Ideological Showdown

docs.abstract: Two-page federal form required to allow religious organizations to opt out of providing contraceptive coverage has become latest focal point in battle to balance religious freedom and women's rights under the Affordable Care Act; organizations say that by signing form, they would be authorizing insurers or plan administrators to pay for contraception in violation of their beliefs; chart highlights and examines form's contents.
docs.snippet: Paperwork required to opt out of coverage is part of a struggle to balance religious freedom and women’s rights.

docs.lead_paragraph: President Obama should resist pressure to weaken a promised executive order to bar federal contractors from discriminating against gay men, lesbians and transgender people.

headline.seo: New Rules Should Ban Discrimination by Federal Contractors

docs.abstract: Editorial urges Pres Obama to resist pressure campaign by some religious groups to weaken promised executive order that would prohibit federal contractors from discriminating against gay men, lesbians and transgender people in their hiring practices; holds that Hobby Lobby ruling, which served to embolden groups, does not justify retreat from order's goal of fairness for all.
docs.snippet: President Obama should resist pressure to weaken a promised executive order to bar federal contractors from discriminating against gay men, lesbians and transgender people.

docs.lead_paragraph: The governor should be ready to step in and end the union-M.T.A. fight before riders face a shutdown.

headline.seo: L.I.R.R. Labor Dispute May Need Cuomo Intervention

docs.abstract: Editorial calls for New York Gov Andrew Cuomo to intervene in labor talks between railroad workers union and Metropolitan Transportation Authority in effort to help resolve dispute and prevent possible strike on Long Island Rail Road; holds that while White House has supported union's proposal for pay increases, issue is state concern rather than a federal one.
docs.snippet: The governor should be ready to step in and end the union-M.T.A. fight before riders face a shutdown.

headline.main: Senators Query Hepatitis C Drug’s High Costs
headline.print_headline: Senators Query Hepatitis C Drug’s High Costs

docs.abstract: Sen Ron Wyden, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, along with one another member, ask Gilead Sciences to defend high cost of its breakthrough treatment for hepatitis; cite massive expanse that $80,000 drug C Sovaldi will represent for federal health care programs.

docs.lead_paragraph: Fertility clinics are using new chromosomal tests to help identify embryos that will give a woman the best shot at a successful pregnancy.

headline.main: Fertility Clinics Scan for the Strongest Embryo
headline.print_headline: A Fitness Test, on the Smallest Scale

docs.abstract: Some fertility clinics are using chromosomal tests to help identify embryos that give a woman the best possible chance of successful pregnancy; techniques can increase low efficiency of in vitro fertilization, and can reduce chance of having twins or triplets, which face higher health risks; critics say the expensive technology is being promoted too heavily without supporting data.
docs.snippet: Fertility clinics are using new chromosomal tests to help identify embryos that will give a woman the best shot at a successful pregnancy.

docs.lead_paragraph: Research shows that what people think now that they will want to do in retirement will probably change. The right planning can prepare for that shift.

headline.main: Saving for Bucket List That’s Likely to Evolve in Years Before Retirement
headline.print_headline: Saving for Bucket List That’s Likely to Evolve in Years Before Retirement

docs.abstract: Ron Lieber Your Money column examines research showing that many people do a poor job of predicting what they will want to do with their leisure time during retirement, making financial planning more difficult; offers advice from experts on how to account for possible shifts in taste when forming a retirement plan.
docs.snippet: Research shows that what people think now that they will want to do in retirement will probably change. The right planning can prepare for that shift.
